column15: An 1959-era building that once served as a printing plant for the Washington Star and then Washington Post, 200 I Street underwent a dramatic renovation from 2011-2012. The new office facility, which was awarded the prestigious LEED Platinum Certification from the US Green Building Council, boasts countless sustainability features -- including a green roof, high efficiency heating and cooling systems, and extensive natural daylighting. The building houses the D.C. Child and Family Services Agency, the Office of the Chief Technology Officer and the Commission on the Arts and Humanities in 2012, and includes a ground floor public art gallery showcasing the cast DCCAH art collection.

column15: Two great academies. One amazing school.' C.W. Harris Elementary School provides students with numerous pathways towards academic and social-emotional growth. They will conduct rigorous instruction in The Shirley Chisholm Early Childhood Academy and The Dr. Carter G. Woodson Upper Elementary Academy taught by highly-qualified teachers. column15: At J.C. Nalle, their goal is for their students to develop the academic and social skills necessary to become responsible citizens in their school and local community. For the past 15 years, the Freddie Mac Corporation has supported their students, alongside the non-profit organization National Center for Children and Families. column15: The Economic Security Administration (ESA) determines eligibility for benefits under the Temporary Cash Assistance for Needy Families (TANF), Medical Assistance, Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP), Child Care Subsidy, Burial Assistance, Interim Disability Assistance, Parent and Adolescent Support Services (PASS) and Refugee Cash Assistance programs. ESA performs monitoring, quality control and reporting functions required by federal law and court orders.

column15: At Leckie Elementary School, they are committed to providing all of their students with a high-quality education. To that end, they have consistently achieved Adequate Yearly Progress under the No Child Left Behind Act. In addition to their core curriculum, their students can take foreign language classes and participate in student government or chorus. They also have an afterschool program, sports teams, an art club, tutoring and a drama club. When asked what they like best about Leckie, students say that they love their engaging teachers and rewarding extracurricular activities.

column15: Ballou Senior High School offers a myriad of academic programs that allow students to explore and reach their maximum potential. These programs include Honors and AP courses, grade-level Academies, an Arts and Technology Academy for students with special needs and the 21st Century Community Learning Center. They also offer the AVID program and school-wide advsiory for students. More than 10 percent of graduating seniors are selected for the Achievers Scholarship from the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation. The 2010 Valedictorian was awarded a Gates Millennium Scholarship and the 2009 Salutatorian was a White House Scholar. Ballou students also benefit from more than 50 partnerships with national and community organizations.

column15: River Terrace Education Campus is a city-wide school, which serves the 1% of the DCPS student population with the greatest needs. This center offers individualized wrap-care services for our students. In addition to differentiated instruction, students receive related services such as Speech and Language, Occupational and Physical Therapy, Vision, Orientation and Mobility, and Audiology. River Terrace also offer aquatic therapy and medical and dental screening services. The mission at River Terrace Education Campus is to promote the individual success of students through diversified instruction, support services, integrated technology, collaboration, parental engagement, and community partnerships that empower all students to reach their full potential as global citizens.

column15: Kenilworth Elementary School is located in the Kenilworth and Eastland Gardens community. They are a school that strongly believes that teamwork and cooperation with parents and the community make a difference in their students' lives. Located high on a ridge overlooking Washington, D.C. from the northeast, the park was designed as the active recreational component of the Fort Lincoln New Town residential community. Conceived under the Johnson administration as part of a 1969 plan to offer racially and economically balanced housing and amenities, the neighborhood development was never fully completed.

The six-acre park occupies one of 68 former Civil War ramparts, now known as the Fort Circle Parks, and was designed to interpret the sites military history and its elevated position. Five open-air structures providing extensive views of the surrounding area from atop the historic earthworks, shaded by clusters of honey locusts designed to grow through the wood-latticed pavilions.

The center of the park sits lower than the perimeter earthworks, with a mix of small berms, lawn, rubberized turf and paved areas for different types of play. Benches on lawn offer seating under shade trees, facing a brick climbing pyramid with a moat. Built into the grade, another play area suggests the historic battlements and has varied scales for climbing, sliding, and scrambling. Permanent seating and tables designed for board games are situated on the perimeter, near a concrete stair-step amphitheater that connects to the school. The parks many levels are all connected by ramps for accessibility.

column15: The Special Education Division of Student Transportation (DOT) is a transportation entity that consistently provides safe and appropriate transportation services to eligible special education students. DOT is responsible for operational policies and procedures, school openings, project management, court reporting, training, training and professional development, compliance with IEP transportation requirements and parent transportation reimbursements. DOT oversees and supervises the day to day operations located at 4 terminals in the Washington DC metropolitan area.

column15: The new Langley Education Campus for Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics (STEM) is a fully modernized campus that provides high quality instruction infused with exposure to real world concepts, inquiry and innovation. Located in Northeast Washington DC, Langley Education Campus is a neighborhood school for students from the NoMA, Eckington, Bloomingdale, and Edgewood communities. Additionally, Langley provides services to students from around the city through the out-of-boundary process and in our citywide Intellectual Disability Program. Our goal at Langley is to ensure that students are inspired to imagine, inquire, and innovate.

The Emery Work Bed Program (EWBP) is specifically tailored to the needs of homeless men who are employed or in job training.

The EWBP can serve up to 100 men. The primary objective is to assist men in sustaining employment and moving into permanent housing. Program participants must be willing to accept case management services, meet with case management staff weekly and develop and follow an Individualized Service Plan (ISP).

column15: McKinley Technology High School is one of five specialized secondary schools in the district. It is the Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics (STEM) high school for the district offering a comprehensive school experience and specialized instruction opportunities in biotechnology, engineering, information technology and mass media technology. McKinleys STEM curriculum, state of the art technology, Advanced Placement offerings and emphasis on critical thinking and problem solving make it particularly desirable for students interested in the math and science fields. Their motto is No excuses. Just solutions!
column162:

Prospect Learning Center is a student-centered, full-time, comprehensive school for students with disabilities, established in 1979. The school provides a supportive and nurturing learning environment designed to accelerate academic achievement. Together, they work to improve their students' organizational and study habits, self-esteem, self-confidence and social skills.

column15: Sherwood Recreation Center is a community recreation center that with facilities that include basketball court, fitness center, gymnasium, kitchen, multipurpose room, and a tennis court.

We provide a wide range of enrichment and extracurricular activities for students, including beginning and intermediate band, chorus, clubs and sports, including cross-country, track and football. Included in their dedicated faculty are a number of teachers who have received or are working towards national board certification, as well as a past recipient of the DCPS Art Teacher of the Year Award. In the 2011-2012 school-year, Stuart-Hobson boasted several city-wide National History Day and Science Fair winners. Their graduates go on to attend the most competitive public and private high schools in DC and ultimately, the most prestigious colleges and universities in the nation.

column15: School-Within-School @ Logan Annex (SWS) is a teacher-directed, Reggio Emilia-inspired school. They are a vibrant early childhood learning environment for prekindergarten and kindergarten children. SWS is housed at the Logan Annex building behind the Logan School on the 200 block of G Street, NE. Their mission is to support and develop childrens potential through a uniquely child-centered, collaborative teaching and learning environment inspired by the philosophy and practice of the Reggio Schools for young children in Reggio Emilia, Italy.

Maury Elementary School is a small community-based school that offers students a personalized learning environment. Through work and in play, students discover their potential, embrace diversity and benefit from strong relationships with staff, parents and volunteers. Maury is committed to providing inquiry-based learning experiences, arts enrichment and academic programs that enhance students growth and development. Parents are always welcome and work closely with teachers to ensure that each child receives the attention he/she needs to succeed. At Maury, they educate the whole child in a safe, multidimensional environment.

column15: Eastern Senior High School provides engaging, college preparatory coursework and extra-curricular learning experiences that ensure all students graduate with the content knowledge, character and confidence to serve as innovative, inclusive global leaders. Eastern will enroll first-time ninth and tenth grade students for the fall of 2012, growing by one grade each year in order to strategically design a rigorous, well-rounded high school experience for every student. The 550 students in the Class of 2015 and 2016, with support from exemplary teachers and a diverse set of community partners, will build upon rich traditions and set a course of excellence on their newly restored, state-of-the-art campus.

column15: Charles H. Houston Elementary School prides itself on offering an excellent educational program that fosters the whole development of each student. They believe that all children can be successful when they learn to recognize their own strengths and needs as well as those of others. At Houston, they strive to educate students so that they will develop into informed citizens who are productive and can make positive contributions in the world they live in.

column15: At Kelly Miller Middle School, their goal is to provide their students with a rigorous and relevant educational experience in an environment that meets each students individual needs. Every student receives quality instruction that supports and maintains high expectations. Their faculty and staff are dedicated to creating an excellent academic experience with the necessary social and behavioral supports for their students. Ultimately, they aim to prepare their students not only for high school, but for their lives beyond the classroom and as leaders of their communities.

Their teachers work diligently to ensure that all students are taught a standards-based curriculum that focuses on developing literacy and numeracy skills, while also developing critical thinking skills. Their goal is to help their students become change agents in their communities and the world at-large. They set extremely high expectations for their students and utilize technology to enrich their strong academic programs. They are a catalyst school, offering an Arts Integration curriculum by weaving the visual and performing arts into the classroom as tools for teaching core subject content.

column15: The New Anacostia Library opened on Monday, April 26, 2010. The library earned a LEED 'Gold' Certification for environmentally sustainable design.The inviting, two-story library is 22,000 square feet and offers a wide range of library services. It features: Separate spaces for adults, teens and children; 40,000 books, CDs, DVDs, and other library materials; childrens program room, comfortable seating for 200 customers, 40 public access computers and free Wi-Fi internet access, mobile laptop cart with 20 computers, a large programming room for up to 100 people, two conference rooms to for up to 14 people, five quiet study rooms for one to two people, and public art by Ward 7 artists. The new library was designed by The Freelon Group.

On March 16, 2009 Jobs Have Priority opened the shelter at 2603 Naylor Rd SE. JHP focuses on helping people transition from dependency to self sufficiency through education, job development and support. The shelter provides shelter for 28 families by supplying them with their own furnished apartment along with weekly case management meetings focused on increasing self-sufficiency. The shelter houses a computer lab equipped with high speed internet and a community room where families can gather for a weekly movie night. Adult residents participate in life skills and employment classes, while children are provided with tutoring and enrichment activities.
column106: Naylor Road Temporary Shelter for Families

column15: Randle Highlands Elementary School represents a partnership of students, faculty and administrators who are united in their commitment to common objectives. Collectively they work to be a positive force in the community that inspires and prepares all students to become contributing and productive members of society. Through a rigorous curriculum, students achieve measurable successes in their academic endeavors. Dedicated and motivated learners engage in hands-on, student-led experiences that are applicable to the global community. Their staff is dedicated to fostering a culture that addresses each child's unique learning style through targeted instruction, community partnerships, school-based initiatives and parental involvement.

column15: Anne Beers Elementary School provides a strong focus on Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics (STEM). They remain the only NASA Explorer School in the District of Columbia. Community and business partnerships enhance and support student learning. A Beers student engages in a variety of learning opportunities which integrate subject matter in a holistic manner. This school year they are enhancing their PBL (Performance Based Learning) opportunities to increase relevance and strengthen the real world connection for their students. Upon promotion from Beers their students will be global citizens who are caring, collaborative, critical in their thinking, solution oriented and able to assume leadership roles. Their faculty and staff are dedicated to their students and their families. At Beers, they help their students understand their responsibility to the world while providing them with an excellent education and in a responsive family-oriented environment.

Orr Elementary School is a DC3 Collaborative School located in Southeast DC. In addition to offering a high-quality core curriculum, their students also have the opportunity to participate in their arts program, library media center, music, computer, art and physical education classes. To supplement their rigorous academic curriculum, they offer a variety of extracurricular activities including their French Language and Culture Program through their partnership with the Alliance Francaise. Their partnership with the Boys and Girls Club of Greater Washington allows them to offer before and after care programs. They have a brand new, state-of-the-art library and a parent center run by their full-time parent coordinator. At Orr, they strive to provide their students with a comprehensive, well-rounded education that prepares them not only for their future academic careers, but also to become productive citizens in the world.

column15: Garfield Elementary School is a School-Wide Application Model (SAM) School. SAM is a general education support that focuses on fully integrating and coordinating resources and services to improve academic and social outcomes for all students. Frequent and on-going assessments help determine the instructional approaches best suited to meet each students needs. They work to create a safe and orderly learning environment and to increase academic achievement for all students. Garfield Elementary School is a Tools of the Mind school. Their early childhood focus is on the importance of self-regulated behavior on increasing academic achievement. This is their second year of implementation. The Garfield Rams strive to be respectful, responsible, and ready in their school work and citizenship.

column15: The Parklands-Turner Neighborhood Library has seen much growth and change over its more than 35-year history. Starting out as a library kiosk in 1976, Parklands-Turner has since served the community as one of four portabranch community libraries built in D.C.. between 1981 and 2009. The portabranch was closed in 2009 to make way for a newer library space, in The Shops at Park Village, across from its former location. The new library offers a great increase in space, with 4,500 square feet, enough room for features such as: 20 public computers, free Wi-Fi Internet access, more books, DVDs and other library materials, space for story time and other library programs, free parking.
This parks facility includes large fields, walking paths and a community garden.

At Tyler, they offer three unique programs that address the needs of each individual student while contributing to a tight-knit school community. Their Spanish immersion program serves approximately 160 students in preschool through 3rd grade. Tyler is also an Arts Integration Catalyst school, which means that students incorporate the arts into all subjects. Finally, Tyler serves a Special Education population that consists primarily of autistic and intellectually disabled students. All three of these programs are compassionate and connected - the values that they try to exemplify and instill in their students at Tyler. Their vision at Tyler is for all students to experience an engaging and rigorous curriculum so they can grow and read at and above grade level. Their mission statement is Tyler grows students, arts, language, technology, global citizens.

column15: Southeast Neighborhood Library, one of three Carnegie-funded libraries in D.C. and the second neighborhood library built, proved to be one of the library system's busiest from its opening on Dec. 8, 1922. The one-story brick building, designed by noted library architect Edward L. Titlton, sits at 403 7th St. SE on an irregularly shaped site in the Capitol Hill National Register District, purchased with $8,360 from Congress, and bolstered by $67,000 in construction funding from the Carnegie Corporation. In 1982, an intensive renovation was undertaken. To serve the community better, a handicap access ramp and elevator were installed, as was new lighting.In the spring of 2007, Southeast Neighborhood Library was the recipient of Library Journal/American Library Association funding and in-kind donations from a variety of library vendors. This resulted in another major interior renovation.

The CC&V Shelter for the homeless was an abandoned federal building that was occupied by Mitch Snyder and other CC&V activisits in 1984. The federal government eventually leased the property to the CC&V for one dollar a day. It was later transferred to the control of the District of Columbia.The 1,350-Bed Federal City Shelter is still the largest and most comprehensive facility of its kind in America. They also provide clothing to their residents. Donors, including stores, contribute thousands of pounds of clothing and shoes to CCNV's residents each year. Surplus clothing is sold in The Treasure Chest Thrift Store when so designated by donors.

column15: One Judiciary Square is a high-rise office building at 441 Fourth Street NW in the Judiciary Square neighborhood of Washington, D.C. Designed by architect Vlastimil Koubek, the building has approximately 10 floors and was in built 1990. Between 1992 and 1999, One Judiciary Square housed the offices of the mayor and Council of the District of Columbia while repairs were made to the historic John A. Wilson Building. One Judiciary Square now houses the offices of prominent municipal government agencies such as the D.C. Board of Elections and Ethics, the Office of the D.C. Attorney General, and the D.C. Office of Zoning. In August 2009, it was one of the first government buildings in Washington to be fitted with a green roof. In addition, the city completed a $7.5 million renovation in September 2011 to improve the building's energy efficiency.

column15: The Henry J. Daly Building is a low rise art deco style building that completed construction in 1941. The building is named for Sergeant Henry J. Daly, a 28-year veteran of the Metropolitan Police Department who was killed November 22, 1994, by an armed intruder in the building. The Daly Building houses most of the administrative units of the MPDC. At Headquarters, individuals can: retrieve copies of police and traffic crash reports, obtain police clearances, register their firearms, register as a known sex and offender. The Daly Building also houses the District's Department of Motor Vehicles Adjudication Services and the probation and parole offices. On the first floor of the building, individuals can: schedule a hearing, attend walk-in parking hearings, make ticket payment plans, and pay tickets.

Be Bilingual. Embrace Diversity. Achieve Excellence. For more than 30 years, Oyster-Adams Bilingual School has served as a model for dual-language education programs (English and Spanish) in the District of Columbia and nationwide. Children learn 50% of their core academics in Spanish and 50% in English. Students are supported by two certified teachers in every classroom who are also native speakers of their target language. The cultural diversity within Oyster-Adams forges long-lasting friendships among students and families from different cultural and linguistic backgrounds, nationalities and socio-economic levels. Oyster-Adams won the TEAM Award for academic achievement in 2010.

column15: Powell Elementary School is a small, community-based school focused on academic success for all. They are the winners of the Fight for Children Rising Star Award. Their mission is for every student to reach high levels of academic achievement. At Powell, their primary focus is on academic rigor, teaching and learning, and educating the whole child in a nurturing community and family-friendly school so that all students are prepared to succeed at the high school and college of their choice. Students have access to excellent teachers and master rigorous standards in literacy, math, science, social studies, the arts, Spanish, health and fitness. They demonstrate their learning through portfolios, extended projects and investigations, performances, as well as on-going assessments. All students also take music, art, physical education and library media classes. Their comprehensive preschool and prekindergarten program features Tools of the Mind Curriculum (Powell was the pilot for DCPS). Through their Dual Language program, students have the opportunity to become biliterate/bilingual in English and Spanish while acquiring the skills they need to live and work with others in a global society.

The Takoma Park neighborhood received the first purpose-built Neighborhood Library in the history of the D.C. Public Library system on November 17, 1911. Prior to receiving funding for the public library branch, Takoma Park residents were served by a private subscription library. The current Takoma Park Branch at 416 Cedar St. N.W. was funded through a $40,000 contribution by philanthropist Andrew Carnegie. One of four Carnegie-funded library buildings in Washington, D.C., the Takoma Park library represented the beginning of a system of branches that today encompasses 25 branch libraries and one central library. The one-story Renaissance Revival style brick building was designed by the Washington-based architectural firm of Marsh & Peter. The building has continuously served this upper-Northwest community since 1911, and remains a community focal point. The Takoma Park Neighborhood Library stands in the Takoma Park National Register Historic District designated in 1983.

column15: At Langdon Education Campus, they serve students in preschool through 8th grade in a learning environment that promotes the acquisition of valuable knowledge and skills and serves as a foundation for each student to progress successfully through all educational levels. Their curriculum consists of a traditional course of study with a focus on science, technology, engineering and math (STEM), which makes education and careers in the sciences more accessible for their students. They foster an ongoing exchange of ideas and resources for their students, parents and educators to achieve their goals.

column15: The Arboretum Recreation Center facilities include a Basketball Court, Multipurpose Room, Parksite, Playground, Tennis Court.

The DC Department of Parks and Recreation (DPR) Chevy Chase modernization project at 41st Street and Livingston Street, NW, is a full site renovation. The new facilities will include new baseball field, new playground, splash park, dark park, and improvements to the recreation center.

Murch's programs and child-centered learning environment make the most of the diverse array of talents and abilities exhibited by all of the children within their community. Using a blend of traditional and innovative educational techniques, Murch develops strong academic skills, promotes civic responsibilities and fosters confidence within each child. Murch students have universal access to internet resources using computers located in every classroom and the Media Center. In addition, teachers take full advantage of the wealth of resources available in and around the nations capital.
column162: Undergoing renovation as of 11/16. (MLA, 11/16)

column15: After several decades of utilizing only volunteer fire companies, an act to organize a paid fire department was approved in 1864 and implemented on September 23, 1871, with a combination of paid and volunteer staff. Today, the DCFD operates 33 Fire Stations located throughout the district in 6 Battalions. Engine Company 31 operates under the command of the 5th Battalion.

column15: District law states that a vehicle is boot-eligible if it has two or more unsatisfied parking and/or photo enforcement tickets that are 60 days old. The Blue Plains Impound and Storage Facility is the long term impound facility used by the District for the storage of scofflaws vehicles.
DC's Police Training Academy rigorously prepares 35-strong classes of cadets for the rigours and challenges of a career in law enforcement.

column15: This building is a former elementary school (Blair Elementary) that was converted into a homeless shelter and clinic operated by the District of Columbia. The Blair Transitional and Rehabilitation Program provides 24-hour residential services to homeless men who are ready to make a change in their lives. Services include substance abuse counseling, case management, employment and housing placement assistance, and meals. The length of the program is 6-9 months, and it is designed to help the men move to independence and self-sufficiency.
This facility includes an outdoor pool, tennis courts, basketball courts and two baseball diamonds.

column15: The new Unified Communications Center (UCC), was opened on September 26, 2006. The Center is a high technology, state-of-the-art call center, housing what were separate call centers for police, fire, EMS, and non-emergency public safety calls and proving integrated services to streamline the continuing issues of emergency preparedness and security. The full redundancy of all mechanical, electrical, and telecommunications systems and the blast-resistant design were important factors for heightened survivability.The communications area is augmented by administrative headquarters space, federal government adjunct facilities, briefing and media centers, training rooms, parking for 272 vehicles, a landscaped terrace, and a 12,000 square foot child development center to serve UCC employees and the neighboring community. In 2007 the UCC was awaded the Washington Building Congress Craftsmanship Award in the Special Construction Category for Acoustical Ceiling Systems.

column15: The present Tenley-Friendship branch of the D.C. Public Library at 4450 Wisconsin Ave. N.W., was dedicated on October 27, 1960. It was designed by architect Clark T. Harmon under the direction of the D.C. Department of Buildings and Grounds and constructed by the B.F. Rodney Company. The library building was erected with funds appropriated under the D.C. Public Works Program, which allotted $333,000 for construction of the two-story steel and brick facility. The library branch is supported by the Friends of Tenley-Friendship Library, the first of such 'friends' groups established in the District of Columbia.

column15: The Jelleff Boys & Girls Club provides a safe and fun place for kids to spend time after school. The Jelleff Club is a full-service, year-round Club offering a variety of programs in sports, education, recreation, and the arts, housed in a facility that includes a gym, game room, teen center, computer lab, outdoor pool, and field. It offers an after school tutoring program, special activities such as yoga, art, hip hop, and hand drumming, as well as Youth leadership groups.

The John A. Wilson Building, popularly known simply as the Wilson Building or the JAWB, houses the offices and chambers of the Mayor and Council of the District of Columbia. Originally called the District Building, it was renamed in 1994 to commemorate former Council Chair John A. Wilson. Completed in 1908, the building is a contributing structure to the Pennsylvania Avenue National Historic Site.In 1995, two-thirds of the Wilson Building was leased to the Federal government for a period 20 years due to the District's inability to pay for needed repairs. However, after the United States Congress approved funds for a major renovation, the District was able to regain use of the entire building.The fully renovated Wilson Building reopened in September 2001.

column15: The Mt. Pleasant Neighborhood Library, opened in May 1925, and is the third oldest public library building still in use in Washington. The library was primarily funded by the Carnegie Corporation and designed by accomplished library architect Edward L. Tilton. In 2008, the library started a major renovation, restoration and expansion. The renovated library reopened Sept. 12, 2012, with improvements include: welcoming spaces and comfortable seating, expanded children's space with a large story time room, dedicated teen space with mac computers, meeting room for 100 people, 50,000 books, DVDs and other library materials, as well as 40 computers plus laptops available for customer use in the library.

column15: Shepherd Elementary School is an International Baccalaureate (IB) school. They aim to develop inquisitive, international-minded learners who think and learn globally and act compassionately. As part of this educational framework, they offer French and Spanish instruction beginning in prekindergarten and they also focus on learning through inquiry-based instruction. Their staff and faculty are extremely dedicated to their students and their school; the average teacher tenure is 12.5 years. They set high expectations for their students and they work collaboratively with all stakeholders to make sure their students receive a solid elementary education foundation.

column15: The Lamond-Riggs Neighborhood Library opened October 24, 1983, on the north side of South Dakota Avenue between Jefferson and Kennedy streets N.E. Situated in the northernmost section of Northeast, the branch was intended to supplement the services of the outgrown Takoma Park Neighborhood Library and to extend library services to a broader community in Northeast. The Lamond-Riggs Library, a $2 million facility, was erected with funds provided in the Public Library's Capital Improvements budget. The two-story, 19,000 square-foot brick building was the first of two D.C. library buildings designed by the minority architectural firm of Bryant and Bryant, Architects, and constructed by A.A. Beiro Construction Company.

They also offer a Parent Academy at Plummer with workshops that teach parents and guardians how to become empowered advocates for their children.

With a demanding educational agenda that builds upon the active engagement of school, parents and community, Miner Elementary School seeks to inspire young learners. They promote academic, social and cultural excellence in a dynamic school environment. Their school is supported by numerous partnerships that assist in the improvement of student performance and educational excellence. Nestled in the Capitol Hill community of northeast Washington, DC, they provide an inspiring, exciting and enthusiastic learning environment, a clean, safe and state of the art facility and a supportive and resourceful educational setting.

New York Avenue Emergency Shelter is an emergency shelter for men over the age of 18. The program offers a hot meal, a shower, a place to stay off of the streets, access to a case manager and a work program to give clients experience in the work environment. We also run a clothing store for free clothing to clients. Shuttle service is offered to several locations in downtown DC. Intake begins at 7 pm each night and the shelter closes at 7 am the next morning.
This shelter serves as a hypothermia shelter during the winter months between October and March when temperatures drop to deadly lows.

column15: At Takoma Education Campus, their motto is Takoma students work hard, get smarter, go to college. Their goal for their students is to have a strong academic foundation that will lead to success in college and beyond. To that end, they have been committed to providing a high-quality education to students in preschool through 8th grade for more than 30 years. Takoma will be the only DCPS PS-8 school that is an Arts Integration school. In addition to their after-school program, they also offer sports and a variety of extracurricular activities for their middle school students.

column15: Cardozo aims to create educational and social experiences that will prepare students with the knowledge and skills necessary for success in the global economy. In addition to a new state-of-the-art Web Design class and lab, Cardozo also offers science and humanities AP courses, technology courses, JROTC, and boys and girls athletics teams. Students enhance their coursework through Saturday Scholars, evening credit recovery and after-school tutoring programs.

column15: The Academies at Anacostia High School underwent academic restructuring in 2009-2010 that resulted in the creation of four distinct learning academies, a thriving online and accelerated learning program and additional CTE programs. These programs provide students personalized, comprehensive instruction and greater individual support. Each academy has its own administrator, counselor, teachers and dean of students. All Academies at Ancostia students have the opportunity to enroll in one of the following career pathways: Certified Nursing Assistant (CNA), Emergency Medical Technician (EMT), Homeland Security and Law Enforcement, or Graphic Design. Students have taken advantage of this academic turnaround and several have been awarded a record number of DC Achievers and Gates Millennium Scholarships during the past three years. On August 27, 2012, students moved into a completely modernized state of the art building equipted and updated with science and computer labs and a media center.

column15: Designed by D.C. Muncipal Architect Nathan C. Wyeth, the two-and-a-half story Georgian Revival-style library building opened on Jan. 27, 1939. In June 2009, the Petworth Neighborhood Library began a two-phase renovation process to update, improve and modernize the historic building. The first phase tackled exterior renovations that included window restoration, improved ADA access and a new cupola and balustrade on the roof. Phase II, which began in November of the same year, improved lighting, restored original finishes and furniture, imporoved elevators, updated bathrooms, and also included environmentally friendly changes that could grant the building LEED Silver or Gold status. The renovated library re-opened on Monday, Feb. 28, 2011.

The new Dorothy I. Height/Benning Neighborhood Library opened in April 2010. The library was designed by architecture firm of Davis Brody Bond Aedas. The two-story, 22,000 square foot library features a flexible design to provide inviting spaces for all. It offers: 40,000 books, DVDs, CDs, and other library materials with space for up to 80,000, children's program room, separate reading areas for adults, teens and children, 32 public access computers with free Wi-Fi Internet access, 8 Mac computers in the teen area, mobile laptop cart with 20 computers, comfortable seating for 200 customers, large program room for up to 100 people, two 12-person conference rooms, parking for 14 vehicles, vending area, and public art by Ward 7 artists.

column15: Whittier Education Campus is a friendly neighborhood school located in a culturally rich community. Their vision is to prepare all Whittier students to become life-long, innovative learners and productive competitors in the 21st century. Their mission is to provide an interactive, hands-on approach to inquiry and project-based learning focused on science, technology, engineering and mathematics. Whittier also offers an engaging athletic program and a fully functioning computer lab for students to enjoy.

column15: Stoddert Elementary School serves approximately 350 students in prekindergarten through 5th grade. The students hail from very diverse backgrounds, representing 26 different countries. They pride themselves on their strong parental involvement and community interest. Their students learn in a beautiful geo-thermal, renewable-energy modernized school, complete with a state-of-the-art gym and cafeteria. They have earned autonomy status after a quality school review by demonstrating an outstanding record of high student achievement. Stoddert Elementary is one of the first schools in the District of Columbia to receive 'Reward School' status based on their students' achievement on the 2012 DC CAS.

column15: The purpose of Somerset Preparatory Academy PCS is to provide an individualized, academically rigorous, and engaging curriculum focusing on the ever-changing needs of our learners. Our educational process encompasses the partnership among the school, family, and community, in order to develop a life long love of learning. We strive to develop students who are self-assured, well-rounded, and prepared for future success. Our three-pronged focus is LEARN: prepare students for college; LIVE: equip students with intellectual, emotional, social, and ethical skills to maximize their individual potential; and LEAD: form confident, self-directed, and responsible life long learners who take an active role in improving the local and global community.

They also offer coursework in Spanish, financial literacy and entrepreneurial exploration and literacy through photography.

column15: At Brent Elementary School, they bring together a diverse learning community of students, staff and families to provide an ethical, personal and academic foundation for success in a global society. The goal is to nurture self-motivated and joyful learners who are creative and critical in their thinking and highly capable in their communication. Their parental involvement, support and leadership create a unique partnership for world-class teaching and learning on Capitol Hill. They are a responsive learning' community committed to each child meeting or exceeding the rigorous Common Core State Standards and DCPS grade-level standards. They utilize Columbia University's Readers and Writers Workshops as their approach to literacy using the best children's literature. Investigations Mathematics provides each Brent mathematician multiple pathways to a personalized mastery of math. Every week young scientists, artists, sports leaders and multilingual students in grades K-5 take Lab Science, Music and Art Studio, Chinese, Museum Studies and Team Sports.

column15: The Georgetown Neighborhood Library was severely damaged by a fire on April 30, 2007. The firm of Martinez & Johnson Architects, in partnership with Hoshide Williams, were hired to design the renovation of this historic building. The renovation restored this neighborhood treasure while adding many modern improvements including: better lighting, dedicated space for teens, improved ADA access, more space, including a new, larger Peabody Room, which houses a special collection of materials on the history of Georgetown. A new outdoor reading terrace overlooking Book Hill Park. A new bright, spacious children's room with a special story time space. Restored woodwork throughout the building.The old mezzanine level was removed, bringing in more light and opening up the first floor to views looking out onto Book Hill Park.

After several decades of utilizing only volunteer fire companies, an act to organize a paid fire department was approved in 1864 and implemented on September 23, 1871, with a combination of paid and volunteer staff. Today, the DCFD operates 33 Fire Stations located throughout the district in 6 Battalions. Engine Company 23 operates under the command of the 6th Battalion.

Lamond Recreation Center is a 14,750 square foot community recreation center and the first LEED Certified public building in the District of Columbia.vSustainable features include storm water management, a vegetated green roof, water efficient landscaping, water use reduction (low flow faucets/fixtures), increased energy efficiency, enhanced building commissioning, construction waste recycling, a bio-pond for water collection and many others. Amenities include a gymnasium, fitness center, and a multipurpose room, meeting space, classrooms, an arts and crafts center, computer lab, pantry/kitchen, an outdoor walking trail, baseball field, volleyball court, tot-lot and on-site parking.

As Washington's largest comprehensive public high school, Woodrow Wilson High School is home to a very diverse student population. In 2011, the entire campus underwent a complete $105 million modernization just in time for their 75th anniversary. More than 9 out of 10 Wilson graduates attend college and members of last year's class were accepted to over 200 universities and junior colleges across 41 states and the District of Columbia and offered over $18 million in scholarships. Wilson currently offers Advanced Placement (AP) college level courses in 27 subject areas as well as six smaller learning communities or academies. In addition, Wilson fields 26 varsity and junior varsity sports teams and boasts over 44 extracurricular clubs and activities.

column15: The Hamilton Recreation Center playground design aims to enhance the play areas while emphasizing the overall diversity of the recreation center. Supported by an active community, Hamilton is in constant use throughout the year. The playground improvements for Hamilton include increasing the size of the 6 - 12 play area long the northeast part of the site by extending the site east towards the existing baseball i eld. A new 2 - 5 play area is proposed adjacent to the 6 - 12 play area. Both of these play areas will include rubberised play surfacing. A new entry gate will be located between the two new play areas. A semi-circular concrete area along with a new concrete path will connect the new gate to the existing recreation center. The existing chain link fence around the entire play areas and recreation center should be removed and replaced as per the plan. The plan aims to reduce the amount of fencing to open up the park and make it more welcoming. Towards the rear of the park, the community has built a tot lot with a variety of play equipment. New rubberized surfacing should be poured around the existing play equipment. The community wishes to include a race track around the play equipment. Additional play equipment should be considered to augment the existing tot-lot in this area as well. Safety lighting should be included as part of the design. A new community garden area is proposed just south of the recreation building. This area will include pine garden boxes to be maintained by the community. The area around the garden boxes should be gravel. A new 10ft square storage shed mounted on a concrete pad should be included in this area. To the east of the existing recreation center building a new shade structure with picnic tables is proposed. This shade structure is envisioned to be made out of wood with a canvas. The shade structure will be mounted on a new concrete pad. In addition to the play area improvements, a new gate will be added leading directly to the courts from Hamilton Street. The existing shuffleboard and four square courts will be replaced as a multi- purpose court with futsal goals and basketball hoops.

column15: At Hendley Elementary School, their goal is to help all of their students learn to think analytically and become independent, well-rounded individuals. They currently serve students in preschool through 5th grade. All of their students take music, art, physical education and library classes as well as their core academic courses. When asked, their students say that one of the things they like best about Hendley are the field trips they take to supplement what they learn in the classroom. For students as well as staff and parents, their school is warm, welcoming place to be.

column15: The Kalorama Recreation Center facilities include a basketball court, community garden, multipurpose room, parksite, and playground.

John H. Ketcham is located in Anacostia within the historic Uniontown area. They are proud of their dedicated community partners and the manner in which they work with their children to enrich their lives and support their staff. They strive to ensure that each child develops academically and socially. They seek to equip students with the skills and high self-esteem needed to be successful in higher education and in a global society. Their motto at Ketcham Elementary School is Together, They Can Make A Difference: Together, They Make Their School Special.

column15: Ludlow-Taylor is a Title I elementary school on Capitol Hill. The focus of their work has been to build the expertise of their teaching staff so that their instructional program is powerful! Their data reflects impressive growth, Kindergarten up through grade 5. Their DC CAS scores moved from 45 percent up to 61 percent in reading and from 53 percent up to 59 percent in math with their intermediate students scoring at the proficient and advanced levels. Their PTA is strong and active and their parents have created a House of Representatives to act as informational liaisons for their many engaged but busy parents. They are an Arts Integration School and their ECE classrooms implement that through Reggio Emilia. Ludlow-Taylor ES is slated for modernization during the upcoming 2013 summer. Come join them - The Best Kept Secret on the Hill!

Malcolm X is a positive force in the community that inspires and equips all students to be contributing and productive members of society. Through a project- and inquiry-based integrated Science, Technology, Engineering and Math (STEM) curriculum, their students achieve measurable success and growth on rigorous academic endeavors. At Malcolm X, they are committed to fostering a culture that addresses each child's unique learning style through targeted instruction, community partnerships, school-based initiatives and parental involvement.

column15: A four-time recipient of the US Department of Education Blue Ribbon School Award, Horace Mann Elementary School combines the intimacy of a one-room schoolhouse with a progressive educational program and the global perspective afforded by their diverse, multi-national population. Committed to teaching and learning, they also believe that a school community must be a place of joy. They embrace academic choice, game-playing and interaction among learners throughout the building. Their faculty also engages in a continual cycle of renewal and improvement as they strive to be highly responsive to their students' needs and passions.

column15: The Martin Luther King Jr. Memorial Library, the central library of the DC Public Library System, opened on August 21, 1972. The world-famous architect Ludwig Mies van der Rohe was commissioned to design the structure, and ground was broken at 9th and G streets in July 1968. Constructed of matte black steel, brick and bronzed-tinted glass, the building provides 400,000 square feet of floor space on four floors above ground and three underground levels. Designated a historic landmark on June 28, 2007, the citys central library houses public service areas, including subject divisions, meeting rooms and exhibition space, as well as the administrative and support services for all public libraries in Washington, D.C.

column15: On September 17, 2012 New Endeavours by Women broke ground on the construction project to renovate and expand the 611 N Street facility that is home to the New Transitions program and administrative offices. The new facility will provide 30 transitional units in clusters of 5-6 bedrooms each for the New Transitions residents. The facility will combine transitional housing and permanent supportive housing for women in one residential space: 20% of units will be permanent supportive housing for senior women with a history of chronic homelessness, and 80% will be transitional housing for adult women over age 18.

column15: The Northeast Neighborhood Library, built in 1929, was the first public library branch to be built in the District entirely with public funds. Congress set aside $35,500 to purchase a site and an additional $150,000 to cover construction costs. Designs for the two-story Georgian Revival-style brick library building were prepared by Albert L. Harris, the city's Municipal Architect. Harris was also responsible for designing some of the original wood furnishings fitted for the interior of the library. In October 2012, Northwest Neighborhood Library began a $10 million historic renovation, which will include new elevators, plumbing, furniture and flooring.

column15: The present building was built under the D.C. Public Works Program at a cost of approximately $450,000. It was designed by Albert Goenner and Associates of Bethesda in collaboration with the D.C. Department of Buildings and Grounds. Minmar Builders of D.C. was the contractor, and construction was supervised by James A. Blaser, Director of the D.C. Department of Buildings and Grounds. The building is modern in appearance, with a facade faced with red brick, ceramic mosaic tile and an entrance area with a large plate glass display window. At the time of its opening, the Palisades Library building was one of the largest in the public library systemm with approximately 20,000 square feet of space and a potential book capacity of 60,000 volumes. The library is situated near the commercial section of MacArthur Boulevard, the principal thoroughfare of the Palisades neighborhood it serves.

column15: The historic Peabody Elementary School building is the early childhood campus of the Capitol Hill Cluster School, serving students in preschool through kindergarten. An arts-integration school, their nurturing faculty is trained and passionate about integrating learning with real life, using different forms of the arts and a hands-on, inquiry-based approach to teaching and learning. They assess each child to learn their strengths and areas for development, and they support their growth with an individualized approach to learning. Their fellow Cluster School students at Stuart-Hobson Middle School come back to Peabody regularly as volunteers and tutors, contributing to their mission of building community responsibility and relationships. They use their edible and ornamental gardens, the Capitol Hill neighborhood and all of Washington, DC as an extension of the classroom, preparing their students to be successful at Watkins Elementary for 1st-5th grade and eventually Stuart-Hobson Middle School for 6th-8th grade.

Although their students hail from different cultural backgrounds, they have formed strong bonds and have created a thriving school community. At Seaton, they have a strong English as a Second Language program that serves students who speak Chinese, Spanish and Amharic. When their students leave Seaton, they should be able to excel in middle school and throughout the rest of their academic careers.

column15: The Juanita E. Thornton/Shepherd Park Neighborhood Library at 7420 Georgia Ave. NW opened on July 29, 1990. The $3.3 million facility was built with funds included in the District's supplemental budget of 1985. The library was the second D.C. library designed by the architectural firm of Bryant and Bryant. The facility consists of a two-story, reinforced concrete structure faced with 'Calvert Rose' brick. The building features an irregular shape, consisting of interlocking geometric shapes that resemble clustered towers and numerous, generously sized windows. The building contains reading rooms for children and adults, audio-visual facilities, an auditorium, several meeting rooms and exhibit space. There space for 48,000 volumes in the book stacks.

column15: The building located at 1125 Spring Road was originally built for the Hebrew Home for the Aged, which occupied the building from 1925 to 1969. Described as being in a pure American style, it was designed by local architect Harry A. Brandt and cost $27,000 to build. Its exterior combined maroon brick with buff limestone trim, including Stars of David that remain today.The property at 1125 Spring Road was sold to the District of Columbia 1968 for $13 Million. While it served as a center for medical services for the homeless after it transfer to the District for many years, today the building is empty.

column15: Waterfront Station is a mixed-use urban center in Southwest Washington, DC. The project includes seven new buildings totaling over 2 million square feet including Class-A office space, new residential units and neighborhood oriented retail in the heart of Southwest. Situated on the Waterfront-SEU Metro station the project features a thriving retail oriented streetscape along the newly re-opened 4th Street all in close proximity to the new baseball district, Arena Stage, the Southwest Waterfront and major destinations throughout the region. Completed in 2010, 1101 4th Street, SW, is home to the Government of the District of Columbia, and features convenient ground floor retail, including Safeway, CVS, Station 4, Z-Burger, Subway, a bank, a drycleaners, and more.

column15: Students who attend H.D. Woodson have the opportunity to participate in the NAF program (Information Technology / Computer Science) and also the city renowned STEM Academy. The school also offers a myriad of AP courses. H.D. Woodson had the most improved graduation rate in the District for the last two years (70% ) and also increased promotion rates at every grade level. The school's sports program continued to be the most dominant in the DC metro area winning the varsity boys football championship for the 3rd straight year and its second consecutive varsity boys basketball championship. The boys varsity basketball ball team also made history by finishing the season undefeated and winning the state championship. The boys varsity basketball team finished the year ranked 8th in the nation.
